[3] Comment on cVDPV
Date: Wed 24 Feb 2021
From: T Jacob John <tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in> [edited]


[My sincere apologies for the delay in posting this update and comment from Dr T Jacob John. - Mod.MPP]

The case-to-infection ratio of wild poliovirus type 2 [WPV2] is in the range of 1 to 1000-2000. So one case of WPV2 polio means 1000-2000 silent infections. cVDPV has a lower risk of paralysis, the case-to-infection ratio may be between 1 to 5000-10 000. That is the reason why we cannot rely on AFP surveillance for detecting the prevalence of cVDPV-2 but need sewage surveillance.

In 2020, if there were 1048 confirmed cases of polio due to cVDPV-2, that means the size of the silent epidemic was at least 1048 x 5000 = 5 240 000 [updating this calculation to 1067 cases, 5 335 000 infections - Mod.MPP]

Waiting for novel OPV [oral poliovirus vaccines] is not enough. There is no guarantee the eradication program can eradicate cVDPV-2 in one or 2 years. If we had 5 million cVDPV infections in 2020, the probability that it will further de-attenuate and become genotypically and phenotypically closer to wild virus than vaccine virus is high. Immediate and widespread IPV [inactivated polio vaccine] by campaign is the necessary intervention now.

If that is not operationally feasible, EPI [Expanded Program on Immunization] must revise its immunisation policy to recommend "at least 2 doses" of IPV, stand-alone or combination vaccine. I say this because "at least 1 dose of IPV" is part of the eradication program.

If stand-alone, then 14 weeks and 9 months of age should be ideal, to match with 2 contacts for other vaccines, or if combination vaccine, 3 doses as per the current EPI schedule. This is ethically necessary. No excuses like high cost or low coverage, etc. should be used to delay this decision. No child ever had polio after 2 well-timed IPV doses or 3 EPI schedule IPV doses. Preventing polio is the primary duty of the eradication program; this will not in any way interfere with the interventions deemed necessary by the eradication program.

--
T Jacob John
439, Civil Supplies Godown Lane
Kamalakshipuram
Vellore, TN 632002
India
<tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in>

[ProMED would like to thank Dr T Jacob John for his very insightful comment. Clearly, the vaccine (OPV) has become a major part of the polio problem globally with cVDPV cases exploding in many countries (see sections [1] and [2] above. The call to change vaccines to IPV should be loud and clear. Arguments on the cost of the change should include calculations of the cost of the cases of cVDPV associated disease and the cost of the repeated mop up outbreak control vaccination campaigns. - Mod.MPP]

